  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I find an engine for an SAE Supra?",
  "response": "Finding an engine for an SAE Supra project involves several steps. Here\u2019s a comprehensive guide to help you source the right engine:\n\n1. **Understand the Requirements**:\n    - **Rules and Regulations**: Check the specific rules set by the SAE for the Supra competition regarding engine specifications. There could be restrictions on engine displacement, power, or type.\n    - **Team Objectives**: Align the engine choice with the team's goals, such as performance targets, reliability, ease of integration, and budget constraints.\n\n2. **Identify Potential Engines**:\n    - **Common Choices**: Many SAE teams choose engines that are small, lightweight, and have a good power-to-weight ratio. Motorcycle engines, such as those from Honda CBRs or Yamaha R6s, are popular due to their compact size and high performance.\n    - **Manufacturers and Models**: Consider engines from manufacturers known for reliability and performance tuning options.\n\n3. **Sourcing the Engine**:\n    - **New Engines**: Contact engine manufacturers directly or through authorized dealers. Brands like Honda, Yamaha, or Suzuki could be options if you coordinate a purchase.\n    - **Used Engines**: Look for used engines through online marketplaces such as eBay, Craigslist, or dedicated motorsport forums. Salvage yards or motorcycle shops might also have options.\n    - **Donor Vehicles**: Consider purchasing a wrecked or otherwise non-roadworthy motorcycle or car to extract the engine.\n\n4. **Budget Considerations**:\n    - Evaluate total cost including purchase, shipping, and any potential rebuilding or modification costs.\n    - Consider potential sponsorships or partnerships with local businesses or engine manufacturers to reduce costs.\n\n5. **Technical Considerations**:\n    - **Integration**: Ensure the engine can be integrated into the project with respect to size, weight distribution, and compatibility with the car\u2019s drivetrain.\n    - **Supporting Systems**: Factor in the need for an appropriate fuel system, cooling system, exhaust, and electronics to support the engine.\n    - **Maintenance and Spares**: Choose an engine for which parts are readily available and that is serviceable within your team\u2019s capabilities.\n\n6. **Documentation and Compliance**:\n    - Make sure to keep thorough documentation of your engine and any modifications for technical inspections during the competition.\n    - Ensure compliance with all safety and technical regulations.\n\n7. **Seek Advice**:\n    - Network with other teams, attend SAE events, or join forums and online groups related to SAE Supra or Formula Student competitions to gather insights and advice.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to find an engine suitable for your SAE Supra project that fits your team\u2019s requirements and resources.",
